'''Eli Katz''' ([[April 6]], [[1920s#1926|1926]] &ndash; [[January 31]], [[2000]]), better known as '''Gil Kane''', was a comic-book artist who illustrated a few comic covers for the [[Star Wars (1977)|Marvel ''Star Wars'']] series. He was also tapped to illustrate [[Dark Horse Comics]]' adaptation of [[Dark Force Rising (comics)|''Dark Force Rising'']], but had to drop out of the project due to scheduling conflicts.

Born in Riga, Latvia, Kane moved with his family to New York in [[1930s#1930|1930]]. His earliest comics work, at the age of 16, was drawing borders and word balloons for already penciled drawings. Kane later began working as an illustrator for [[Wikipedia:DC Comics|DC Comics]] and worked on many of their titles over several decades. Some of his more notable work was done in the late 1950s recreating DC's [[Wikipedia:Green Lantern|Green Lantern]] and [[Wikipedia:The Atom|The Atom]]. Kane also worked for [[Marvel Comics]], illustrating several [[Wikipedia:Spider-Man|Spider-Man]] stories and regularly producing covers for various series including ''[[Star Wars]]''. In 2000, Kane died of complications from cancer.{{Mediacat|imagecat=images by Gil Kane}}

